    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-04-04T11:47:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-04-04T10:50:00-05:00" n="56"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d56">
                <head>56. Summary of Conclusions of a Washington Special Actions Group Meeting<note
                        n="1" type="source" xml:id="d56fn1">Source: Library of Congress, Manuscript
                        Division, <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> Papers, Box
                            <gloss target="#t_TS1">TS</gloss> 78, National Security Council,
                        Committees and Panels, Washington Special Actions Group, Mar. 1971–Apr.
                        1972. Top Secret; Sensitive. The meeting took place in the White House
                        Situation Room.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1972-04-04T10:50:00-05:00" to="1972-04-04T11:47:00-05:00">April 4,
                            1972, 10:50–11:47 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Vietnam</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>Chairman</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>State</item>
                    <item>John N. Irwin</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWH1">William Sullivan</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Defense</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RK1">Kenneth Rush</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_NGW1">Warren Nutter</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>Adm. <persName corresp="#p_MTH1">Thomas H. Moorer</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Lt. Gen. <persName corresp="#p_VJW1">John Vogt</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HRM1">Richard Helms</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>William Newton (only for Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HRM1">Helms</persName>’
                        briefing)</item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>Maj. Gen. <persName corresp="#p_HAM1">Alexander Haig</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KRT1">Richard Kennedy</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_NJD1">John Negroponte</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mark Wandler</item>
                </list>
                <p rend="center">SUMMARY OF CONCLUSIONS</p>
                <p>It was agreed that: <list>
                        <item>—The State Department should send a message to <gloss target="#t_Amb1"
                                >Amb</gloss>. <persName corresp="#p_GGM1">Godley</persName> in Laos,
                            telling him to ask for whatever air support he needs, regardless of what
                            he thinks may be available.</item>
                        <item>—The Defense Department should draw up an operations plan for hitting
                            the storage facilities at Dong Hoi, augment the fire support ships off
                            the Vietnamese coast and transfer the <gloss target="#t_IRONHAND1"
                                >Ironhand</gloss> squadron of F–105s to Vietnam.</item>
                        <item>—Additional <gloss target="#t_F4Phantom1">F–4</gloss>s should be sent
                            to Vietnam. Dr. <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> will
                            obtain Presidential guidance on whether to send Marine <gloss
                                target="#t_F4Phantom1">F–4</gloss>s from Japan or Air Force <gloss
                                target="#t_F4Phantom1">F–4</gloss>s from the U.S.</item>
                        <item>—The State Department spokesman should again hit hard at the North
                            Vietnamese violations of the Geneva Accords and the 1968 understandings.
                            He should also mention the massive Soviet supply effort.</item>
                        <item>—Clark MacGregor and David Abshire should begin contacting members of
                            Congress, seeking support for the Administration position.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>[Omitted here are the minutes of the meeting.]</p>
            </div>
